block.p: Colleen Ellen Dunphy, the daughter of Joanne and Edward P. Dunphy of White Plains, was married there yesterday to Nicholas Rhinelander King, the son of Mary G. King of Westfield, N.J., and the late Rev. David R. King. The Rev. Patrick J. Dunne performed the ceremony at Our Lady of Sorrows Roman Catholic Church, with the Rev. Jonathan L. King, an Episcopal priest and an uncle of the bridegroom, taking part.

The bride, 26, will continue to use her name professionally. She is an account manager at D'Arcy Masius Benton & Bowles, the New York advertising agency. She graduated from Georgetown University. Her father is the corporation counsel for the City of White Plains. Her mother teaches the first grade at the Ridgeway School in White Plains.

King, an Episcopal priest and an uncle of the bridegroom, taking part.

The bride, 26, will continue to use her name professionally. She is an account manager at D'Arcy Masius Benton & Bowles, the New York advertising agency. She graduated from Georgetown University. Her father is the corporation counsel for the City of White Plains. Her mother teaches the first grade at the Ridgeway School in White Plains.

The bridegroom, 39, works at CMG Communications, a New York advertising agency at which he is a vice president and the executive producer for radio and television advertising production. He graduated from Lehigh University and received a master's degree in film from Columbia. His father was the rector of St. John's Episcopal Church in Elizabeth, N.J.
The bridegroom's great-great-grandfather Frederic W. Rhinelander was a trustee and the president of the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
